If we add a non-tree edge $(u, v)$ with weight $w$, it forms a unique cycle with the path $d(u, v)$. The weight of this cycle is $w + d(u, v)$.
For the condition to hold, we must have $w + d(u, v) \equiv 0 \pmod 2$.
This means $d(u, v) \equiv w \pmod 2$.

If this condition holds for *every* non-tree edge added, does it guarantee that *every* cycle remains even? Yes, because any cycle is formed by adding a set of edges, and if the fundamental cycles (formed by adding one non-tree edge) are all even, then any combination of these cycles will also have an even weight (since $0+0=0 \pmod 2$).

